    <exercise xml:id="x2_1_3">
      <p>
        Express the following functions in the form <m>u(x,y) + iv(x,y)</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(z)=z^3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(z)=\overline{z}^2 + (2-3i)z</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(z) = \frac{1}{z^2}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x2_1_4">
      <p>
        Express the following functions in the polar coordinate form <m>u(r, \theta) + iv(r, \theta )</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(z) =z^5+\overline{z}^5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(z)=z^5 + \overline{z}^3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For what values of <m>z</m> are the above expressions valid?
              Why?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x2_1_5">
      <p>
        Let <m>f(z) = f(x+iy) = e^x\cos y+ie^x\sin y</m>.
        Find
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(0)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(i\pi)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(i\frac{2\pi}{3})</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(2+i\pi )</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(3\pi i)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Is <m>f</m> a one-to-one function?
              Why or why not?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="x2_1_6">
      <p>
        For <m>z \ne 0</m>,
        let <m>f(z) =f(x+iy) =\frac{1}{2} \ln (x^2+y^2) +i\arctan \frac{y}{x}</m>.
        Find
        <ol>
          <li>
